This project aims to eventually implement a web app that allows users to interactively experiment with the behavior of systems of interacting particles. The interactions in question correspond to minimizing the reisz energy of the system, which is basically a generalization of the type of "repulsive forces that scale at an inverse power of distance" behavior exhibited by charged particles. One of the things gained in the generalization is the ability to impose a desired density on the particles such that they will distribute themselves to match the relative values any given function over the space they inhabit, while still keeping optimal distance apart from eachother. The idea is that users will see a window that contains a bunch of points (with a wraparound structure to avoid clumping at the boundaries), that will be able to move around in real time as they attempt to keep away from eachother. There are several parameters that users can tweak in real time and see the points shift and change behavior accordingly. There is a pause and play button for the points' movement, tools to place and delete individual points, optional statistics about the total energy of the system, and an fps indicator. 